roaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Array","Hash Table","Two Pointers","Binary Search"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Given two integer arrays `nums1` and `nums2`, sorted in non-decreasing order, return *the **minimum integer common** to both arrays*. If there is no common integer amongst `nums1` and `nums2`, return `-1`.\n\nNote that an integer is said to be **common** to `nums1` and `nums2` if both arrays have **at least one** occurrence of that integer.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: nums1 = [1,2,3], nums2 = [2,4]\nOutput: 2\nExplanation: The smallest element common to both arrays is 2, so we return 2.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: nums1 = [1,2,3,6], nums2 = [2,3,4,5]\nOutput: 2\nExplanation: There are two common elements in the array 2 and 3 out of which 2 is the smallest, so 2 is returned.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= nums1.length, nums2.length <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= nums1[i], nums2[j] <= 10⁹`\n\n- Both `nums1` and `nums2` are sorted in **non-decreasing** order.","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Array","Hash Table","Two Pointers","Binary Search"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Easy","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"Given two integer arrays `nums1` and `nums2`, sorted in non-decreasing order, return *the **minimum integer common** to both arrays*. If there is no common integer amongst `nums1` and `nums2`, return `-1`.\n\nNote that an integer is said to be **common** to `nums1` and `nums2` if both arrays have **at least one** occurrence of that integer.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: nums1 = [1,2,3], nums2 = [2,4]\nOutput: 2\nExplanation: The smallest element common to both arrays is 2, so we return 2.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: nums1 = [1,2,3,6], nums2 = [2,3,4,5]\nOutput: 2\nExplanation: There are two common elements in the array 2 and 3 out of which