mpossible to make the two arrays equal.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `n == nums1.length == nums2.length`\n\n- `2 <= n <= 10⁵`\n\n- `0 <= nums1[i], nums2[j] <= 10⁹`\n\n- `0 <= k <= 10⁵`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Array","Math","Greedy"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Medium","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"You are given two integer arrays `nums1` and `nums2` of equal length `n` and an integer `k`. You can perform the following operation on `nums1`:\n\n- Choose two indexes `i` and `j` and increment `nums1[i]` by `k` and decrement `nums1[j]` by `k`. In other words, `nums1[i] = nums1[i] + k` and `nums1[j] = nums1[j] - k`.\n\n`nums1` is said to be **equal** to `nums2` if for all indices `i` such that `0 <= i < n`, `nums1[i] == nums2[i]`.\n\nReturn *the **minimum** number of operations required to make *`nums1`* equal to *`nums2`. If it is impossible to make them equal, return `-1`.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: nums1 = [4,3,1,4], nums2 = [1,3,7,1], k = 3\nOutput: 2\nExplanation: In 2 operations, we can transform nums1 to nums2.\n1st operation: i = 2, j = 0. After applying the operation, nums1 = [1,3,4,4].\n2nd operation: i = 2, j = 3. After applying the operation, nums1 = [1,3,7,1].\nOne can prove that it is impossible to make arrays equal in fewer operations.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: nums1 = [3,8,5,2], nums2 = [2,4,1,6], k = 1\nOutput: -1\nExplanation: It can be proved that it is impossible to make the two arrays equal.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `n == nums1.length == nums2.length`\n\n- `2 <= n <= 10⁵`\n\n- `0 <= nums1[i], nums2[j] <= 10⁹`\n\n- `0 <= k <= 10⁵`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-operations-to-make-array-equal-ii/","problemName":"Minimum Operations to Make Array Equal II","problemNumber":2541,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"You are given two integer arrays `nums1` and `nums2` of equal length `n` and an integer `k`. You can perform the following operation on `nums1`:\n\n- Choose two indexes `i` and `j` and increment `nums1[i]` by `k` and decrement `nums1[j]` by `k`. In other words, `nums1[i] = nums1[i] + k` and `nums1[j] = nums1[j] - k`.\n\n`nums1` is said to be **equal** to `nums2` if for all indices `i` such that `0 <= i < n`, `nums1[i] == nums2[i]`.\n\nReturn *the **minimum** number of operations required to make *`nums1`* equal to *`nums2`. If it is impossible to make them equal, return `-1`.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: nums1 = [4,3,1,4], nums2 = [1,3,7,1], k = 3\nOutput: 2\nExplanation: In 2 operations, we can transform nums1 to nums2.\n1st operation: i = 2, j = 0. After applying the operation, nums1 = [1,3,4,4].\n2nd operation: i = 2, j = 3. After applying the operation, nums1 = [1,3,7,1].\nOne can prove that it is impossible to make arrays equal in fewer operations.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: nums1 = [3,8,5,2], nums2 = [2,4,1,6], k = 1\nOutput: -1\nExplanation: It can be proved that it is impossible to make the two arrays equal.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `n == nums1.length == nums2.length`\n\n- `2 <= n <= 10⁵`\n\n- `0 <= nums1[i], nums2[j] <= 10⁹`\n\n- `0 <= k <= 10⁵`","type":"text"}],"difficulty":"Medium","examples":[],"paidOnly":false,"problem":"You are given two integer arrays `nums1` and `nums2` of equal length `n` and an integer `k`. You can perform the following operation on `nums1`:\n\n- Choose two indexes `i` and `j` and increment `nums1[i]` by `k` and decrement `nums1[j]` by `k`. In other words, `nums1[i] = nums1[i] + k` and `nums1[j] = nums1[j] - k`.\n\n`nums1` is said to be **equal** to `nums2` if for all indices `i` such that `0 <= i < n`, `nums1[i] == nums2[i]`.\n\nReturn *the **minimum** number of opera