 **XOR** `s[j]`).\n\nFor example, if `s = \"0110\"`, you can choose `i = 0` and `j = 2`, then simultaneously replace `s[0]` with (`s[0]` **OR** `s[2]` = `0` **OR** `1` = `1`), and `s[2]` with (`s[0]` **XOR** `s[2]` = `0` **XOR** `1` = `1`), so we will have `s = \"1110\"`.\n\nReturn `true` *if you can make the string *`s`* equal to *`target`*, or *`false`* otherwise*.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: s = \"1010\", target = \"0110\"\nOutput: true\nExplanation: We can do the following operations:\n- Choose i = 2 and j = 0. We have now s = \"0010\".\n- Choose i = 2 and j = 1. We have now s = \"0110\".\nSince we can make s equal to target, we return true.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: s = \"11\", target = \"00\"\nOutput: false\nExplanation: It is not possible to make s equal to target with any number of operations.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `n == s.length == target.length`\n\n- `2 <= n <= 10⁵`\n\n- `s` and `target` consist of only the digits `0` and `1`.","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/apply-bitwise-operations-to-make-strings-equal/","problemName":"Apply Bitwise Operations to Make Strings Equal","problemNumber":2546,"problemSlug":"apply-bitwise-operations-to-make-strings-equal","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":2546,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Array","Hash Table","Dynamic Programming","Counting"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"You are given an integer array `nums` and an integer `k`.\n\nSplit the array into some number of non-empty subarrays. The **cost** of a split is the sum of the **importance value** of each subarray in the split.\n\nLet `trimmed(subarray)` be the version of the subarray where all numbers which appear only once are removed.\n\n- For example, `trimmed([3,1,2,4,3,4]) = [3,4,3,4].`\n\nThe **importance value** of a subarray is `k + trimmed(subarray).length`.\n\n- For example, if a subarray is `[1,2,3,3,3,4,4]`, then trimmed(`[1,2,3,3,3,4,4]) = [3,3,3,4,4].`The importance value of this subarray 