** 0\n\n**Explanation:**\n\n- Change `nums[1]` and `nums[2]` to 1 so that `nums` becomes [1,1,1].\n\n- The sum of maximum absolute difference and minimum absolute difference is 0.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `3 <= nums.length <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= nums[i] <= 10⁹`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-score-by-changing-two-elements/","problemName":"Minimum Score by Changing Two Elements","problemNumber":2567,"problemSlug":"minimum-score-by-changing-two-elements","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":2567,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Array","Bit Manipulation","Brainteaser"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"You are given a **0-indexed** integer array `nums`.\n\nWe say that an integer x is **expressible** from `nums` if there exist some integers `0 <= index1 < index2 < ... < indexk < nums.length` for which `nums[index1] | nums[index2] | ... | nums[indexk] = x`. In other words, an integer is expressible if it can be written as the bitwise OR of some subsequence of `nums`.\n\nReturn *the minimum **positive non-zero integer** that is not **expressible from *`nums`.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: nums = [2,1]\nOutput: 4\nExplanation: 1 and 2 are already present in the array. We know that 3 is expressible, since nums[0] | nums[1] = 2 | 1 = 3. Since 4 is not expressible, we return 4.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: nums = [5,3,2]\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: We can show that 1 is the smallest number that is not expressible.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= nums.length <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= nums[i] <= 10⁹`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Array","Bit Manipulation","Brainteaser"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Medium","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"You are given a **0-indexed** integer array `nums`.\n\nWe say that an integer x is **expressible** from `nums` if there exist some integers `0 <= index1 < index2 < ... < indexk < nums.length` for which `nums[index1] | nums[index2] | ... | nums[indexk] = x`. In other words, an integer is expressible if it can be written as the bitwise OR of some subsequence of `nums`.\n\nReturn *the minimum **positive non-zero integer** that is not **expressible from *`nums`.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: nums = [2,1]\nOutput: 4\nExplanation: 1 and 2 are already present in the array. We know that 3 is expressible, since nums[0] | nums[1] = 2 | 1 = 3. Since 4 is not expressible, we return 4.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: nums = [5,3,2]\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: We can show that 1 is the smallest number that is not expressible.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= nums.length <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= nums[i] <= 10⁹`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-impossible-or/","problemName":"Minimum Impossible OR","problemNumber":2568,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"You are given a **0-indexed** integer array `nums`.\n\nWe say that an integer x is **expressible** from `nums` if there exist some integers `0 <= index1 < index2 < ... < indexk < nums.length` for which `nums[index1] | nums[index2] | ... | nums[indexk] = x`. In other words, an integer is expressible if it can be written as the bitwise OR of some subsequence of `nums`.\n\nReturn *the minimum **positive non-zero integer** that is not **expressible from *`nums`.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: nums = [2,1]\nOutput: 4\nExplanation: 1 and 2 are already present in the array. We know that 3 is expressible, since nums[0] | nums[1] = 2 | 1 = 3. Since 4 is not expressible, we return 4.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: nums = [5,3,2]\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: We can show that 1 is the smallest numb